ote. Drawing on global developments in jurisprudence and penal policy, it examines the background to, and wider significance of, this change in the law. Using the Irish experience to examine the issue in a wider context, this book argues that the legal position concerning the voting rights of the imprisoned reveals wider historical, political and social influences in the treatment of those confined in penal institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrisonersxSuffragezIreland. 0aPrisonersxSuffrage. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aIreland.  aPenal History.  aPenal Policy.  aPrisoner Enfranchisement.  aPrisoners' Rights.1 aBehan, Cormac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610172340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101723423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101723/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles